  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Spectral Analysis and the Frequency Domain\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.hero}\n",
        "**Part IV. Frequency-Domain and Multiresolution Methods**  \n",
        "**Chapter goal:** learn how to describe second-order dependence by frequency rather than by lag. We develop periodic signals, aliasing, random sinusoidal models, spectral distributions, spectral densities, spectra of ARMA models, and AI-assisted interpretation of frequency-domain evidence.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Learning objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "After studying this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. explain the difference between time-domain and frequency-domain views of a time series;\n",
        "2. interpret frequency, period, amplitude, and phase in a discrete-time sequence;\n",
        "3. explain aliasing and the Nyquist frequency;\n",
        "4. show that random sinusoidal models can be stationary;\n",
        "5. define the spectral distribution and spectral density of a stationary process;\n",
        "6. use the identity between autocovariance and spectral density;\n",
        "7. interpret $f(\\omega)$ as variance per frequency;\n",
        "8. derive spectra of white noise, AR(1), MA(1), and causal ARMA models;\n",
        "9. connect spectral peaks with oscillatory behavior in the time domain;\n",
        "10. use AI tools to formulate hypotheses about periodicity while verifying them with mathematics and code.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.1 Why frequency-domain thinking?\n",
        "\n",
        "The earlier chapters used the **time domain**. In the time-domain approach, the central question is:\n",
        "\n",
        "> How does the present depend on the past?\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, an AR(1) model says\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\phi X_{t-1}+W_t.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a rule for moving forward in time. The model describes how the current observation is generated from past observations and new noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "The **frequency-domain** approach asks a different question:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Which oscillations explain the variation in the series?\n",
        "\n",
        "Many time series contain repeated patterns: daily electricity demand, annual climate cycles, weekly web traffic, business cycles, speech waveforms, sensor vibrations, and seasonal sales. Instead of regressing $X_t$ on $X_{t-1},X_{t-2},\\ldots$, spectral analysis studies how much variance is associated with low, medium, or high frequencies.\n",
        "\n",
        "A rough translation is:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Time-domain language | Frequency-domain language |\n",
        "|---|---|\n",
        "| dependence across lags | variance across frequencies |\n",
        "| autocovariance $\\gamma(h)$ | spectral density $f(\\omega)$ |\n",
        "| AR/MA recursions | filters and frequency response |\n",
        "| slow ACF decay | strong low-frequency power |\n",
        "| alternating signs | strong high-frequency power |\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Same information, different coordinates\n",
        "For a stationary process, the autocovariance function and the spectral density are Fourier-transform pairs. They are two coordinate systems for the same second-order information.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.2 Period, frequency, amplitude, and phase\n",
        "\n",
        "A basic periodic component can be written as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mu_t=A\\cos(2\\pi \\omega t+\\varphi),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $A$ is the amplitude;\n",
        "- $\\omega$ is the frequency, measured in cycles per time step;\n",
        "- $1/\\omega$ is the period, measured in time steps per cycle;\n",
        "- $\\varphi$ is the phase shift.\n",
        "\n",
        "If $\\omega=1/12$, then the period is $12$. For monthly data, this corresponds to one cycle per year. If $\\omega=1/7$, then the period is $7$. For daily data, this corresponds to weekly seasonality.\n",
        "\n",
        "The phase parameter can be removed from the nonlinear expression using a trigonometric identity:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "A\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t+\\varphi)\n",
        "=A\\cos(\\varphi)\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)-A\\sin(\\varphi)\\sin(2\\pi\\omega t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus we may write\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "A\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t+\\varphi)\n",
        "=\\beta_c\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)+\\beta_s\\sin(2\\pi\\omega t),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\beta_c=A\\cos(\\varphi),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\beta_s=-A\\sin(\\varphi).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is important computationally: once the frequency $\\omega$ is fixed, fitting a sinusoidal component becomes an ordinary linear regression problem.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example: regression on sinusoids\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\beta_0+\\beta_c\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)+\\beta_s\\sin(2\\pi\\omega t)+E_t.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf{z}_t=\\begin{bmatrix}1\\\\ \\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)\\\\ \\sin(2\\pi\\omega t)\\end{bmatrix},\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\boldsymbol{\\beta}=\\begin{bmatrix}\\beta_0\\\\ \\beta_c\\\\ \\beta_s\\end{bmatrix}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\boldsymbol{\\beta}^{\\top}\\mathbf{z}_t+E_t.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a fixed $\\omega$, ordinary least squares estimates $\\boldsymbol{\\beta}$. The fitted amplitude and phase can be recovered from\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{A}=\\sqrt{\\widehat{\\beta}_c^2+\\widehat{\\beta}_s^2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The phase is recovered up to the sign convention used for the sine term."
      ],
      "id": "c992f12d"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch12-sinusoid-regression\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Fitting a sinusoidal component by linear regression.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "rng = np.random.default_rng(7339)\n",
        "n = 180\n",
        "t = np.arange(n)\n",
        "omega = 1 / 30\n",
        "\n",
        "x = 2.0 + 1.5 * np.cos(2 * np.pi * omega * t + 0.8) + 0.5 * rng.normal(size=n)\n",
        "\n",
        "Z = np.column_stack([\n",
        "    np.ones(n),\n",
        "    np.cos(2 * np.pi * omega * t),\n",
        "    np.sin(2 * np.pi * omega * t),\n",
        "])\n",
        "beta_hat = np.linalg.lstsq(Z, x, rcond=None)[0]\n",
        "x_hat = Z @ beta_hat\n",
        "amp_hat = np.sqrt(beta_hat[1]**2 + beta_hat[2]**2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Estimated coefficients:\", beta_hat.round(3))\n",
        "print(\"Estimated amplitude:\", round(amp_hat, 3))\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(t, x, label=\"observed\", alpha=0.7)\n",
        "plt.plot(t, x_hat, label=\"fitted sinusoid\", linewidth=2)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Sinusoidal regression at a fixed frequency\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch12-sinusoid-regression",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 12.3 Aliasing in discrete time\n",
        "\n",
        "In continuous time, many different frequencies can be observed. In discrete time, we only observe the signal at integer times. This creates an important phenomenon called **aliasing**.\n",
        "\n",
        "For integer $t$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\cos(2\\pi \\omega t)=\\cos(2\\pi (1-\\omega)t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore frequencies $\\omega$ and $1-\\omega$ generate the same observed cosine sequence at integer times. For example, $\\omega=0.25$ and $\\omega=0.75$ are indistinguishable if the data are observed only at $t=0,1,2,\\ldots$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Because of aliasing, we usually restrict attention to the fundamental range\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "-\\frac{1}{2}<\\omega\\leq \\frac{1}{2},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "or equivalently\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "0\\leq \\omega\\leq \\frac{1}{2}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "for one-sided plots of real-valued data. The frequency $1/2$ is the **Nyquist frequency**.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Aliasing warning\n",
        "A high-frequency continuous signal can look like a lower-frequency discrete sequence when sampled too slowly. Spectral analysis always depends on the sampling rate.\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "3f64e687"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch12-aliasing-example\n",
        "#| fig-cap: 'Aliasing: two different continuous frequencies agree at integer time points.'\n",
        "\n",
        "fine = np.linspace(0, 8, 1000)\n",
        "obs = np.arange(0, 9)\n",
        "\n",
        "w1 = 0.25\n",
        "w2 = 0.75\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(fine, np.cos(2*np.pi*w1*fine), label=r\"$\\omega=0.25$\")\n",
        "plt.plot(fine, np.cos(2*np.pi*w2*fine), \"--\", label=r\"$\\omega=0.75$\")\n",
        "plt.scatter(obs, np.cos(2*np.pi*w1*obs), zorder=3, label=\"integer samples\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"cosine value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Aliasing in discrete-time observations\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch12-aliasing-example",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
