      "source": [
        "## 12.4 Random sinusoidal processes\n",
        "\n",
        "A deterministic sinusoid is not a typical stationary stochastic process. However, randomizing the coefficients gives a useful stationary model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=A\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)+B\\sin(2\\pi\\omega t),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "E[A]=E[B]=0,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\operatorname{Var}(A)=\\operatorname{Var}(B)=\\sigma^2,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\operatorname{Cov}(A,B)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "E[X_t]=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For lag $h$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "\\gamma(h)\n",
        "&=\\operatorname{Cov}(X_{t+h},X_t) \\\\\n",
        "&=E[X_{t+h}X_t] \\\\\n",
        "&=\\sigma^2\\cos(2\\pi\\omega h).\n",
        "\\end{aligned}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus $\\gamma(h)$ depends only on the lag $h$, not on time $t$. Therefore $\\{X_t\\}$ is weakly stationary.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "## Why random coefficients matter\n",
        "A deterministic cosine has a time-varying mean. A random-amplitude cosine with zero-mean coefficients has constant mean and lag-only covariance. This is one reason random sinusoidal representations are natural in stationary time-series theory.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "More generally, let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\sum_{j=1}^m \\left[A_j\\cos(2\\pi\\omega_j t)+B_j\\sin(2\\pi\\omega_j t)\\right],\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where the coefficients are uncorrelated, have mean zero, and satisfy\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{Var}(A_j)=\\operatorname{Var}(B_j)=\\sigma_j^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\sum_{j=1}^m \\sigma_j^2\\cos(2\\pi\\omega_j h).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The autocovariance function is a sum of cosines. Each frequency contributes part of the variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.5 Autocovariance and spectral representation\n",
        "\n",
        "For a stationary process, the autocovariance function is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\operatorname{Cov}(X_{t+h},X_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The spectral representation theorem says that there exists a unique nondecreasing function $F$ on $[-1/2,1/2]$, called the **spectral distribution function**, such that\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\int_{-1/2}^{1/2} e^{2\\pi i\\omega h}\\,dF(\\omega).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The total mass of $F$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(1/2)-F(-1/2)=\\gamma(0)=\\operatorname{Var}(X_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This result is the frequency-domain analogue of saying that covariance matrices must be positive semidefinite. The function $F$ distributes the variance of the process across frequencies.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Discrete spectral components\n",
        "\n",
        "For a random sinusoidal process, the spectral distribution has jumps at the sinusoidal frequencies. A process with a strong deterministic or nearly deterministic periodic component often produces sharp spectral peaks.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Continuous spectral components\n",
        "\n",
        "For ARMA-type processes, the spectral distribution is usually continuous. In this case we can write\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dF(\\omega)=f(\\omega)d\\omega,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $f$ is the **spectral density**.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.6 Spectral density\n",
        "\n",
        "If the autocovariance function is absolutely summable,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\sum_{h=-\\infty}^{\\infty}|\\gamma(h)|<\\infty,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then the spectral density is defined by the Fourier series\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\omega)=\\sum_{h=-\\infty}^{\\infty}\\gamma(h)e^{-2\\pi i\\omega h},\n",
        "\\qquad -\\frac{1}{2}<\\omega<\\frac{1}{2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The inverse relation is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\int_{-1/2}^{1/2}e^{2\\pi i\\omega h}f(\\omega)\\,d\\omega.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $h=0$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(0)=\\operatorname{Var}(X_t)=\\int_{-1/2}^{1/2}f(\\omega)\\,d\\omega.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This identity gives the most important interpretation:\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Interpretation of the spectral density\n",
        "The spectral density $f(\\omega)$ describes how the variance of a stationary time series is distributed over frequencies. Large $f(\\omega)$ means that oscillations near frequency $\\omega$ explain a relatively large amount of variation.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Basic properties\n",
        "\n",
        "For a real-valued stationary process with absolutely summable autocovariance:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. $f(\\omega)\\geq 0$;\n",
        "2. $f(\\omega)=f(-\\omega)$;\n",
        "3. $f(\\omega+1)=f(\\omega)$;\n",
        "4. $f$ completely determines $\\gamma$;\n",
        "5. for a Gaussian stationary process, $f$ determines the full finite-dimensional distributions.\n",
        "\n",
        "The evenness $f(\\omega)=f(-\\omega)$ means that real-valued processes have symmetric spectra.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.7 Interactive spectral explorer\n",
        "\n",
        "The following interactive demonstration combines two sinusoidal components with noise. Move the frequency, amplitude, and noise sliders. Notice that the time plot can look complicated, but the spectrum often reveals the hidden frequencies.\n",
        "\n",
        "<div class=\"interactive-card\">\n",
        "<div class=\"controls\">\n",
        "<label>Frequency 1 $\\omega_1$ <input id=\"ch12_f1\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.02\" max=\"0.48\" step=\"0.01\" value=\"0.08\"></label>\n",
        "<label>Amplitude 1 <input id=\"ch12_a1\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.0\" max=\"4.0\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"2.0\"></label>\n",
        "<label>Frequency 2 $\\omega_2$ <input id=\"ch12_f2\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.02\" max=\"0.48\" step=\"0.01\" value=\"0.22\"></label>\n",
        "<label>Amplitude 2 <input id=\"ch12_a2\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.0\" max=\"4.0\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"1.0\"></label>\n",
        "<label>Noise level <input id=\"ch12_noise\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.0\" max=\"2.0\" step=\"0.1\" value=\"0.5\"></label>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "<div id=\"ch12_signal_plot\" style=\"height:340px;\"></div>\n",
        "<div id=\"ch12_spectrum_plot\" style=\"height:340px;\"></div>\n",
        "<p class=\"caption\">The spectrum shown here is a simple finite-sample periodogram-style display. Chapter 13 develops the DFT, FFT, and periodogram carefully.</p>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "\n",
        "<script>\n",
        "(function(){\n",
        "  function seededNoise(n, scale){\n",
        "    // deterministic pseudo-noise so the display changes smoothly when sliders move\n",
        "    var out = [];\n",
        "    var seed = 7339;\n",
        "    for(var i=0; i<n; i++){\n",
        "      seed = (1664525 * seed + 1013904223) % 4294967296;\n",
        "      var u1 = (seed + 1) / 4294967297;\n",
        "      seed = (1664525 * seed + 1013904223) % 4294967296;\n",
        "      var u2 = (seed + 1) / 4294967297;\n",
        "      var z = Math.sqrt(-2 * Math.log(u1)) * Math.cos(2 * Math.PI * u2);\n",
        "      out.push(scale * z);\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    return out;\n",
        "  }\n",
        "\n",
        "  function computeSpectrum(y){\n",
        "    var n = y.length;\n",
        "    var freqs = [];\n",
        "    var power = [];\n",
        "    for(var k=1; k<=Math.floor(n/2); k++){\n",
        "      var re = 0;\n",
        "      var im = 0;\n",
        "      for(var t=0; t<n; t++){\n",
        "        var angle = -2 * Math.PI * k * t / n;\n",
        "        re += y[t] * Math.cos(angle);\n",
        "        im += y[t] * Math.sin(angle);\n",
        "      }\n",
        "      freqs.push(k/n);\n",
        "      power.push((re*re + im*im)/n);\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    return {freqs: freqs, power: power};\n",
        "  }\n",
        "\n",
        "  function update(){\n",
        "    var n = 160;\n",
        "    var t = Array.from({length:n}, (_,i)=>i);\n",
        "    var f1 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_f1').value);\n",
        "    var f2 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_f2').value);\n",
        "    var a1 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_a1').value);\n",
        "    var a2 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_a2').value);\n",
        "    var noise = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_noise').value);\n",
        "    var eps = seededNoise(n, noise);\n",
        "    var y = t.map(function(i){\n",
        "      return a1*Math.cos(2*Math.PI*f1*i) + a2*Math.sin(2*Math.PI*f2*i + 0.7) + eps[i];\n",
        "    });\n",
        "    var spec = computeSpectrum(y);\n",
        "\n",
        "    Plotly.newPlot('ch12_signal_plot', [{\n",
        "      x: t,\n",
        "      y: y,\n",
        "      mode: 'lines',\n",
        "      name: 'time series'\n",
        "    }], {\n",
        "      title: 'Time-domain view',\n",
        "      margin: {t: 45, r: 20, b: 45, l: 55},\n",
        "      xaxis: {title: 'time'},\n",
        "      yaxis: {title: 'value'}\n",
        "    }, {displayModeBar: false, responsive: true});\n",
        "\n",
        "    Plotly.newPlot('ch12_spectrum_plot', [{\n",
        "      x: spec.freqs,\n",
        "      y: spec.power,\n",
        "      type: 'bar',\n",
        "      name: 'power'\n",
        "    }], {\n",
        "      title: 'Frequency-domain view',\n",
        "      margin: {t: 45, r: 20, b: 45, l: 55},\n",
        "      xaxis: {title: 'frequency', range: [0, 0.5]},\n",
        "      yaxis: {title: 'relative power'}\n",
        "    }, {displayModeBar: false, responsive: true});\n",
        "  }\n",
        "\n",
        "  ['ch12_f1','ch12_a1','ch12_f2','ch12_a2','ch12_noise'].forEach(function(id){\n",
        "    document.getElementById(id).addEventListener('input', update);\n",
        "  });\n",
        "  update();\n",
        "})();\n",
        "</script>\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.8 White noise spectrum\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $W_t\\sim WN(0,\\sigma^2)$. Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\begin{cases}\n",
        "\\sigma^2, & h=0,\\\\\n",
        "0, & h\\neq 0.\n",
        "\\end{cases}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\omega)=\\sum_{h=-\\infty}^{\\infty}\\gamma(h)e^{-2\\pi i\\omega h}=\\sigma^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "White noise has a flat spectrum. Every frequency contributes equally. This explains the term **white** noise: it is analogous to white light, which contains all visible frequencies."
      ],
      "id": "4de311aa"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch12-white-noise-spectrum\n",
        "#| fig-cap: White noise has approximately flat spectral power, up to sampling variability.\n",
        "\n",
        "from scipy.signal import periodogram\n",
        "\n",
        "rng = np.random.default_rng(2026)\n",
        "n = 512\n",
        "w = rng.normal(0, 1, size=n)\n",
        "freqs, power = periodogram(w, scaling=\"density\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(freqs, power)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"frequency\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"periodogram\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"A finite-sample spectrum of white noise\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch12-white-noise-spectrum",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The periodogram fluctuates substantially even for white noise. This is not a contradiction. The flat spectrum is a population statement. Chapter 13 explains why raw periodograms are noisy and why smoothing is often needed.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.9 AR(1) spectrum\n",
        "\n",
        "Consider the causal AR(1) model\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\phi X_{t-1}+W_t,\n",
        "\\qquad |\\phi|<1,\n",
        "\\qquad W_t\\sim WN(0,\\sigma^2).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The autocovariance is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\gamma(h)=\\frac{\\sigma^2\\phi^{|h|}}{1-\\phi^2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Its spectral density is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\omega)=\\frac{\\sigma^2}{1-2\\phi\\cos(2\\pi\\omega)+\\phi^2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This formula has a useful interpretation:\n",
        "\n",
        "- If $\\phi>0$, nearby observations tend to have the same sign. The process is smooth. The spectrum is largest near $\\omega=0$, a low frequency.\n",
        "- If $\\phi<0$, nearby observations tend to alternate signs. The process is rough. The spectrum is largest near $\\omega=1/2$, a high frequency.\n",
        "\n",
        "<div class=\"interactive-card\">\n",
        "<div class=\"controls\">\n",
        "<label>AR(1) coefficient $\\phi$ <input id=\"ch12_phi\" type=\"range\" min=\"-0.95\" max=\"0.95\" step=\"0.01\" value=\"0.70\"></label>\n",
        "<span id=\"ch12_phi_label\"></span>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "<div id=\"ch12_ar1_time\" style=\"height:320px;\"></div>\n",
        "<div id=\"ch12_ar1_spec\" style=\"height:320px;\"></div>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "\n",
        "<script>\n",
        "(function(){\n",
        "  function noise(n){\n",
        "    var out = [];\n",
        "    var seed = 12012;\n",
        "    for(var i=0; i<n; i++){\n",
        "      seed = (1103515245 * seed + 12345) % 2147483648;\n",
        "      var u1 = (seed + 1) / 2147483649;\n",
        "      seed = (1103515245 * seed + 12345) % 2147483648;\n",
        "      var u2 = (seed + 1) / 2147483649;\n",
        "      out.push(Math.sqrt(-2*Math.log(u1))*Math.cos(2*Math.PI*u2));\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    return out;\n",
        "  }\n",
        "  var eps = noise(240);\n",
        "  function update(){\n",
        "    var phi = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ch12_phi').value);\n",
        "    document.getElementById('ch12_phi_label').innerHTML = ' value: ' + phi.toFixed(2);\n",
        "    var n = 220;\n",
        "    var x = Array(n).fill(0);\n",
        "    for(var t=1; t<n; t++){\n",
        "      x[t] = phi*x[t-1] + eps[t];\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    var time = Array.from({length:n}, (_,i)=>i);\n",
        "    var m = 300;\n",
        "    var freq = [];\n",
        "    var spec = [];\n",
        "    for(var k=0; k<=m; k++){\n",
        "      var w = 0.5*k/m;\n",
        "      freq.push(w);\n",
        "      spec.push(1 / (1 - 2*phi*Math.cos(2*Math.PI*w) + phi*phi));\n",
        "    }\n",
        "    Plotly.newPlot('ch12_ar1_time', [{x:time, y:x, mode:'lines', name:'AR(1)'}], {\n",
        "      title:'Simulated AR(1) path',\n",
        "      margin:{t:45, r:20, b:45, l:55},\n",
        "      xaxis:{title:'time'},\n",
        "      yaxis:{title:'value'}\n",
        "    }, {displayModeBar:false, responsive:true});\n",
        "    Plotly.newPlot('ch12_ar1_spec', [{x:freq, y:spec, mode:'lines', name:'spectrum'}], {\n",
        "      title:'Theoretical AR(1) spectral density, up to scale',\n",
        "      margin:{t:45, r:20, b:45, l:55},\n",
        "      xaxis:{title:'frequency', range:[0,0.5]},\n",
        "      yaxis:{title:'spectral density'}\n",
        "    }, {displayModeBar:false, responsive:true});\n",
        "  }\n",
        "  document.getElementById('ch12_phi').addEventListener('input', update);\n",
        "  update();\n",
        "})();\n",
        "</script>"
      ],
      "id": "857039e6"
    },
