      "source": [
        "## 12.12 Low frequency, high frequency, and time-domain appearance\n",
        "\n",
        "The shape of a spectrum has direct time-domain meaning.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Low-frequency dominance\n",
        "\n",
        "A series dominated by low frequencies changes slowly. It may look smooth, persistent, or trend-like over short windows. Positive AR coefficients often create strong low-frequency power.\n",
        "\n",
        "### High-frequency dominance\n",
        "\n",
        "A series dominated by high frequencies changes direction quickly. It may look jagged or alternating. Negative AR coefficients and negative MA coefficients can create high-frequency power.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Narrow spectral peaks\n",
        "\n",
        "A narrow peak indicates a strong oscillation near a particular period. For example, a peak near $\\omega=1/12$ suggests a period of $12$ time steps.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Broad spectral regions\n",
        "\n",
        "A broad region of elevated spectral density suggests variability spread over a range of frequencies rather than one clean periodic component."
      ],
      "id": "ff95f439"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
