        "## 12.13 Spectral analysis and stationarity\n",
        "\n",
        "Classical spectral density is a property of a stationary process. This matters.\n",
        "\n",
        "If a series has a deterministic trend, the low-frequency region can be dominated by the trend. If a series has changing variance, a single spectrum may average together different regimes. If a series has changing frequencies over time, a global spectrum may hide the time-local structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "A practical workflow is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. plot the time series;\n",
        "2. check for trend, seasonality, variance changes, and outliers;\n",
        "3. transform or difference if needed;\n",
        "4. examine the ACF and PACF;\n",
        "5. examine frequency-domain evidence;\n",
        "6. connect spectral features to time-domain models or scientific explanations.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Do not skip EDA\n",
        "A spectral peak is not automatically a meaningful cycle. It may be caused by trend, sampling artifacts, missing data patterns, calendar effects, or preprocessing choices.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.14 From spectra to filters\n",
        "\n",
        "A linear filter transforms a time series into another time series:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Y_t=\\sum_{j=-\\infty}^{\\infty}a_jX_{t-j}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "If $X_t$ has spectral density $f_X(\\omega)$, then under suitable summability conditions, $Y_t$ has spectral density\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_Y(\\omega)=|A(\\omega)|^2 f_X(\\omega),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "A(\\omega)=\\sum_{j=-\\infty}^{\\infty}a_j e^{-2\\pi i\\omega j}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is the frequency response of the filter.\n",
        "\n",
        "This explains why moving averages smooth a series: they reduce high-frequency power. We will return to filters, FFT computation, and wavelets in Chapters 13 and 14."
      ],
      "id": "4f12655c"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch12-moving-average-filter-spectrum\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A moving-average filter suppresses high frequencies.\n",
        "\n",
        "omega = np.linspace(1e-4, 0.5, 500)\n",
        "\n",
        "def ma_filter_gain(m):\n",
        "    numerator = np.sin(np.pi * m * omega)\n",
        "    denominator = m * np.sin(np.pi * omega)\n",
        "    return (numerator / denominator)**2\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "for m in [3, 7, 15]:\n",
        "    plt.plot(omega, ma_filter_gain(m), label=f\"window m={m}\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"frequency\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(r\"$|A(\\omega)|^2$\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Frequency response of simple moving-average filters\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch12-moving-average-filter-spectrum",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
