      "source": [
        "## 12.15 AI-assisted spectral modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "AI tools can be useful for brainstorming explanations of spectral features, generating code, and checking interpretations. But frequency-domain analysis is easy to overinterpret. Students should use AI as a critic, not as an oracle.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-ai}\n",
        "## AI-assisted study box: spectral interpretation prompt\n",
        "Use the following prompt after producing a time plot, ACF, and spectrum.\n",
        "\n",
        "> I have a stationary time series with the following evidence: [describe time plot], [describe ACF], [describe spectral peaks]. Propose three possible data-generating explanations. For each explanation, state one mathematical model, one diagnostic that could refute it, and one possible artifact caused by sampling or preprocessing. Do not choose a final model until the diagnostics are checked.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Verification checklist for AI output\n",
        "\n",
        "When an AI assistant proposes a spectral explanation, verify:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Frequency-to-period conversion:** if the peak is at $\\omega$, the period is $1/\\omega$.\n",
        "2. **Sampling rate:** the interpretation uses the correct time unit.\n",
        "3. **Aliasing:** no conclusion relies on a frequency beyond the Nyquist limit.\n",
        "4. **Stationarity:** trend and changing variance were considered.\n",
        "5. **Model link:** the proposed time-domain model has a spectrum consistent with the observed one.\n",
        "6. **Validation:** forecasting or classification performance is checked out of sample.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.16 Python workflow: from time plot to spectrum\n",
        "\n",
        "The following workflow is a template. It simulates a stationary series with two periodic components and AR noise, then compares the time-domain and frequency-domain views."
      ],
      "id": "8a23ef4b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch12-full-workflow\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A complete first spectral workflow for simulated data.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "from scipy.signal import periodogram, welch\n",
        "from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf\n",
        "\n",
        "rng = np.random.default_rng(8)\n",
        "n = 512\n",
        "t = np.arange(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "# AR(1) noise\n",
        "eta = rng.normal(scale=0.7, size=n)\n",
        "u = np.zeros(n)\n",
        "for i in range(1, n):\n",
        "    u[i] = 0.6 * u[i-1] + eta[i]\n",
        "\n",
        "x = 1.8*np.cos(2*np.pi*(1/32)*t + 0.5) + 0.9*np.sin(2*np.pi*(1/8)*t) + u\n",
        "\n",
        "freq_p, power_p = periodogram(x - x.mean(), scaling=\"density\")\n",
        "freq_w, power_w = welch(x - x.mean(), nperseg=128, scaling=\"density\")\n",
        "acf_vals = acf(x, nlags=40, fft=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(t, x)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Time plot\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.stem(np.arange(len(acf_vals)), acf_vals)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"lag\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"sample ACF\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Sample ACF\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(freq_p, power_p, alpha=0.45, label=\"raw periodogram\")\n",
        "plt.plot(freq_w, power_w, linewidth=2, label=\"Welch smoothed estimate\")\n",
        "plt.xlim(0, 0.5)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"frequency\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"spectral power\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Frequency-domain diagnostics\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch12-full-workflow",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "In this example, the true periods are $32$ and $8$. The corresponding frequencies are $1/32$ and $1/8$. The spectral plot should show elevated power near those frequencies, while the AR noise adds low-frequency structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.17 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Confusing period and frequency.** A frequency of $0.05$ means a period of $20$, not $0.05$ time units.\n",
        "2. **Ignoring the sampling rate.** A weekly cycle means different things for hourly, daily, and monthly data.\n",
        "3. **Reading too much from a raw periodogram.** Raw periodograms are noisy. Use smoothing or repeated evidence.\n",
        "4. **Applying spectral density theory to nonstationary data without caution.** Trend and changing variance can dominate the spectrum.\n",
        "5. **Forgetting aliasing.** Frequencies outside the fundamental range are not separately identifiable from discrete observations.\n",
        "6. **Treating a spectral peak as causal evidence.** A peak suggests periodic structure, not necessarily a scientific cause.\n",
        "7. **Using random train-test splits after spectral feature extraction.** Frequency-domain features must be evaluated with time-aware validation.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.18 Mini project: detect hidden cycles\n",
        "\n",
        "Choose or simulate a time series with at least one hidden periodic component. Your report should include:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. a time plot;\n",
        "2. an ACF plot;\n",
        "3. a raw periodogram or smoothed spectral estimate;\n",
        "4. a table translating the top spectral peaks into periods;\n",
        "5. a proposed time-domain explanation;\n",
        "6. one diagnostic that could refute your explanation;\n",
        "7. a short AI-assisted critique paragraph, including what you accepted and what you rejected.\n",
        "\n",
        "A good project does not merely say “there is a peak.” It explains what the peak means, why it may be real, and why it may be an artifact.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.19 Exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Frequency and period.** For each frequency $\\omega=1/4,1/7,1/12,1/24$, compute the period. Give one real-world example for each.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Aliasing.** Show that for integer $t$,\n",
        "\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "   \\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)=\\cos(2\\pi(1-\\omega)t).\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "\n",
        "   Explain why this matters for sampled data.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Random sinusoid stationarity.** Let\n",
        "\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "   X_t=A\\cos(2\\pi\\omega t)+B\\sin(2\\pi\\omega t),\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "\n",
        "   where $A$ and $B$ are uncorrelated, mean zero, and have variance $\\sigma^2$. Prove that $\\{X_t\\}$ is weakly stationary and compute $\\gamma(h)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **White noise spectrum.** Starting from the autocovariance of white noise, derive $f(\\omega)=\\sigma^2$.\n",
        "\n",
        "5. **AR(1) interpretation.** For $\\phi=0.8$ and $\\phi=-0.8$, determine whether the spectrum is larger near $\\omega=0$ or near $\\omega=1/2$. Explain the time-domain behavior.\n",
        "\n",
        "6. **MA(1) derivation.** Derive the MA(1) spectral density\n",
        "\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "   f(\\omega)=\\sigma^2(1+\\theta^2+2\\theta\\cos(2\\pi\\omega)).\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "\n",
        "7. **ARMA formula.** For an ARMA(1,1) model\n",
        "\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "   (1-\\phi B)X_t=(1+\\theta B)W_t,\n",
        "   $$\n",
        "\n",
        "   write its spectral density.\n",
        "\n",
        "8. **Simulation.** Simulate an AR(1) process with $\\phi=0.9$ and another with $\\phi=-0.9$. Plot the time series and periodograms. Explain how the plots match the theory.\n",
        "\n",
        "9. **Spectral peak.** A daily time series has a spectral peak at $\\omega=1/7$. What period does this correspond to? What diagnostic would help determine whether this is a genuine weekly cycle?\n",
        "\n",
        "10. **AI critique.** Ask an AI assistant to interpret a periodogram from a simulated series with known frequencies. Identify one correct statement, one incomplete statement, and one statement that required mathematical verification.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.20 Chapter checklist\n",
        "\n",
        "By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "- [ ] explain frequency-domain analysis in your own words;\n",
        "- [ ] convert between frequency and period;\n",
        "- [ ] explain aliasing and the Nyquist frequency;\n",
        "- [ ] derive the autocovariance of a random sinusoid;\n",
        "- [ ] define spectral distribution and spectral density;\n",
        "- [ ] state the Fourier-pair relationship between $\\gamma(h)$ and $f(\\omega)$;\n",
        "- [ ] interpret the integral of $f(\\omega)$ as variance;\n",
        "- [ ] derive spectra for white noise, AR(1), and MA(1);\n",
        "- [ ] write the spectral density of a causal ARMA model;\n",
        "- [ ] use Python to compute and interpret spectral diagnostics;\n",
        "- [ ] use AI assistance while checking stationarity, aliasing, and model assumptions.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 12.21 Further reading\n",
        "\n",
